"script": "Look up at the Sun, and you're not seeing it as it is now. You're seeing it as it was eight minutes ago, because that's how long its light takes to reach you. Light is fast, but space is enormous. The next nearest star you spot at night left its surface over four years ago. And some galaxies you can see are showing you light that started traveling before Earth even existed. This means every time you glance up, you're staring deep into the past. The night sky is a museum of dead and ancient light.",
